==Old English==

===Etymology===
From Germanic, from the Indo-European ''*sed-'' ‘sit’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[sitta]], Old High German [[sizzan]] (German [[sitzen]]), Old Saxon [[sittian]] (Dutch [[zitten]]), Old Norse [[sitja]] (Swedish [[sitta]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌹𐍄𐌰𐌽]].  The IE root is also the source of Armenian [[nstim]] ‘I sit’, Old Irish [[saidid]] (Irish [[suigh]]), Greek [[ἕζεσθαι]], Latin [[sedere]], Old Slavic ''sěděti'' (Russian [[сидеть]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'sittan/

===Verb===
'''sittan''' (class V strong: '''sitt''' ‘he sits’; '''sæt''' ‘he sat’; '''sǣton''' ‘they sat’; '''ġeseten''' past participle)
# to [[sit]]

